result.execSummary:
The defendant Dale Alan Kitchenmaster Jr. was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of Methamphetamine, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(g).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: If probation is revoked, any jail sentence the defendant receives in this matter will be ordered consecutive to all other sentences.

miscConds.notes:
1) The defendant must provide DNA and pay the surcharge; the analysis may be expunged upon application to the Department of Justice. 
2) All costs, fees, and other surcharges have been paid in full from the bond funds posted in this matter. Court waived $18.
Defendant shall not use or possess firearms for life.

1) The defendant shall maintain absolute sobriety- no use or possession of any illegal drugs, paraphernalia, or controlled substances without a valid prescription. 
2) Defendant shall not vote in any election until their civil rights are restored.
The defendant shall obtain his GED.
The defendant must complete an AODA and comply with any treatment that may be recommended.

1) The defendant shall undergo regular drug testing.  For each drug test that returns a positive result for methamphetamine use, the defendant shall sit 30 days of conditional jail per positive test- without good time credit or Huber privileges.  
2) If the defendant satisfies all conditions of probation, he may petition to discharge off of probation after 1 year.

Burnett County cases 22TR46 and 22TR47 were DRI.

records.addlTxt:
9:11 AM Cases 22CF27, 22TR47, and 22TR46 called together.  Prosecuting attorney James Jay Rennicke Esq in court for the State of Wisconsin.  Defendant Dale Alan Kitchenmaster Jr. in court.  Attorney Alysja Otten in court for Dale Alan Kitchenmaster Jr.  Case is on for Plea/Sentencing Hearing.  Agreement is recited by Attorney Otten: def pleading to Ct 1: Poss meth, cts 2-5 and uncharged read-in to be DRI, joint rec of 2 yrs probation; TR matters also to be DRI.  Atty Otten files PLQ.  Discussion of the fact that there are multiple cases between two different judges; def understands how the global offer works in light of that, wishes to proceed with the plea hearing.  Court asks def if they understand the agreement.  Def does.  Court reviews Def's constitutional rights.  Def understands that def is waiving those rights by entering into agreement today.  Court asks Def if they understand Court is not bound by agreement, and could order maximum penalties.  Def understands.  Court asks for plea. Def enters a plea of Guilty.  Court finds def is making plea knowingly, intelligently and voluntarily.  Court finds a factual basis to accept the plea.  Court finds defendant guilty of Count 1: Possession of methamphetamine and orders a JOC; Counts 2-5, 22TR46, 22TR47, and an uncharged incident are DRI.  DA asks Court to accept agreement.  Defense attorney asks Court to accept agreement.  Def makes a statement to the Court.  
Court orders: 2 yrs probation
Conditions of probation: 
The defendant shall maintain absolute sobriety. No use or possession of any illegal drugs, paraphernalia, or controlled substances without a valid prescription. Regular drug testing; for any drug tests positive for methamphetamine- must sit 30 days conditional jail per positive test. The defendant must complete an AODA and comply with any treatment that may be recommended.  Obtain a GED.  If def satisfies all conditions of probation, may petition to discharge early after 1 year of probation.  $500 court costs (waives $18 and the bond will be applied to pay this in full).  Defendant shall not use or possess firearms for life. Defendant shall not vote in any election until their civil rights are restored.  DNA to be provided to the Sheriff before leaving the building.  Any jail sentence he receives in this case (if revoked) to be consecutive to all other sentences.
Appeal rights provided.
